With Bitcoin, pay and sell without banks
The opposite is true of current currency exchanges based on central banks, identified transactions and processing costs between stakeholders.
Moreover, as is often the case in these technologies, a political vision is palpable: the conviction that the current monetary system, made up of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files from peer to peer.
Some 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers on the network.
A small thousand websites accept bitcoins as donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, after reaching a peak of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, dropped to 2 dollars, five months later, before returning today around 10 dollars (prices are recorded on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing very impressive, compared to world trade in real currency or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) took an interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency such as "credits", used to advance in a video game that you win by playing or can buy (and sometimes trade in return).
The social network Facebook has also developed this kind of system.
Each time, however, a central authority controls and processes trade.
With Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are both depository of the book of accounts, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is actually made between two email addresses in the same way as an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a double key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is also possible to make sure that the bitcoins exchanged exist in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction into this book.
It involves solving a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner, a sort of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file hash phase, that is, the transformation of a large file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before "hashing" the whole.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other nodes easily check that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any change would change the footprint.
If, to fraud, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other left orphaned because the two have different prints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to one hundred millionth, leaving a margin...
The difficulty of the challenge is also met with each increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and bitcoins in stolen deposits.
"The flaw used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who just launched Paymium, a real currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also mentions the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this defect.
Weighted actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blog platform, accept them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the book and showed that nearly 80% of bitcoins do not circulate.
In November, "giant balances" were launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, also author of an educational book on this currency, believes a lot in the potential of this technology as a network of transactions.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (in real currency) or a contactless mobile payment, but he uses Bitcoin to validate transactions, which thus return cheaper.
The carrier also manages his identity and can therefore be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement among merchants, who do not need to install new terminals or software.
All they need to do is provide an address that a phone can "photograph and recognize," says Pierre Noizat, who ensures that thousands of users are there.
There is a general movement to challenge hierarchical systems for more horizontal systems.
"It will take time for Bitcoin to impose itself, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, in its report, plans to re-evaluate the various risks, which are now considered to be high, in the event of the success of this currency.
We left Afghanistan.
And then what?
French troops left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans are expected to follow at the end of 2014.
It is time for the Afghan army to regain its territory and for the Afghans to choose their future, without expecting anything from us.
It is above all the Afghan peasants that we have punished by seeing them as terrorists.
And we ourselves, with our 88 soldiers killed, and the wounded, the maimed.
The Taliban are composed of foreign extremists, former refugee leaders in Pakistan, but often peasants who refuse the foreign armed presence, as in the Soviet era.
They want to defend their ancient and archaic traditions, even if they have been joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
Tolerated, sometimes assisted by local insurgents, these will no longer be so when Westerners become more discreet.
The departure of the French troops from the Nijrab base, which I observed from the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French credits, was in order.
The convoys of trucks and armoured personnel returned to Kabul without being attacked, overflew by helicopters.
There will be no Taliban raid on Kabul by the end of 2014.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
Kabul was then empty, the country with fire and blood as a result of the struggles between different factions.
Their takeover of the country was then perceived as a sort of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women have paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants, who have been overtaken by the Al-Qaeda organization, but their situation has not improved these days.
Former Mujahedin, Afghan government and current Taliban join in the desire to keep women in a lower position.
The main notables of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They turned into businessmen, seizing government land and selling it to refugees who had returned from Iran and Pakistan, benefiting from huge American subcontracts.
They were demeaned; most of them did not fight themselves.
People, as I have heard in the countryside, aspire to a government that is not made up of thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as will those who have been able to benefit from the American broads: capital flight is considerable.
Young people are tired of war and its ideologies.
They came together with the modern world during their exiles in Iran or Pakistan, they appreciated the benefits.
About 65% of the population is under 25 years of age; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one fifth of the total population.
In cities, government schools are full of girls and boys.
It will be necessary to provide work for these young people who will no longer want to go back to the obscurantism of the former parties or to the corruption of certain leaders.
All, including armed opponents, are fond of mobile phones; television, and its Turkish soap operas that present a modern world, are followed everywhere.
The army is now present.
Will the authorities who are going to order it be considered legitimate?
Former anti-Soviet commanders are already concerned about rebuilding provincial militias, which will escape central power.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local identities, should be able to benefit from some decentralization, like the Western nations, but the United States wanted to transform it into a centralized state, with strong presidential power, abolishing the post of Prime Minister that existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign controls, especially in the elections scheduled for April 2014.
But his country has been dependent on foreign aid since the 1950s and long before.
No industry has been restarted, no dams are in repair, no major irrigation system is repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing except fruit and vegetables is produced.
Priority is left to private initiative.
In a country ruined by 30 years of war, government control over infrastructure would have been necessary.
There has been widespread noise that Afghanistan has enormous mineral wealth.
This only added to the feeling that the Westerners were only there to take it.
Without energy to process iron ore or copper on site, or means of transport to export it through the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have already almost left the Mes Aynak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to search the huge Buddhist site and remain the province's largest employers.
Afghanistan and Pakistan, which are heavily dependent on imports and exports, will also need to re-establish normal relations.
The departure of French fighting troops ended on 20 November.
The new cooperation treaty provides for the continuation of traditional aids: lycée for girls, boys, French department at the university, French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the Archaeological Delegation.
Since 2009, in an attempt to "win hearts and minds" and to carry out the impossible task of bringing together aid and offensive actions, a service of "civil-military actions" of the Ministry of Defence (Cimic), abolished in 2012, has carried out, and commissioned by a small French NGO, numerous works of collective interest and actions of agricultural rehabilitation in dozens of mountain villages.
This work, which is greedy of local labour, has helped to contain the insurgency: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and an increase in cultivable areas.
What will we leave to remember, after two billion euros of military spending?
A much smaller budget would contribute to the improvement of local living conditions, which are very hard in these valleys often located at more than 2,000 metres above sea level.
The Embassy received dozens of written requests for small agricultural achievements from local communities in Kapisa province.
In order for them to free themselves from the insurgency led by foreign groups, which farmers have told me they wish, small, well-controlled civilian aid that directly affects them should be maintained.
A Forceps Constitution in Egypt
It's a new poker shot by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants it full powers, it has decided to play its game.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the following day.
Just a week ago, the Head of State granted this House an additional two months to finish its work.
Egypt has been relying almost two years on a provisional text, several times amended which undermines institutional stability and leads to legal imbroglios.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President perseveres in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "traitor his word" and "pietine the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to put an end to the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible, by accelerating the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time which obliges the Brothers to give up their plans to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, this is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy as the protest rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote favorably, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
All the more so since this use of a hasty vote is due to the Egyptian people's ultimatum: "Would you vote for my text, or I will keep the full powers", these are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It was in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this Constituent Assembly, with a large Islamist majority, voted yesterday.
Most Liberals were missing.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they had slammed the door, believing that they had not been able to put forward their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it was most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Commentators also had fun that only one of the differences of the day was expressed around... the time of prayer, as some members of the committee felt that the pendulum of the constituent was wrongly settled.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
As a matter of concern, Article 2 remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a major claim, hoped to be able to replace "the principles" with "the rules", which would have allowed a stricter application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and their respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," the liberals reply, who see it as just a touch of communication.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
These include article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the compliance of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the people called to pronounce themselves are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the first fruits of a theocracy."
The Liberals' fears are further exacerbated by the fact that the next president of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"For the time being, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of civil status.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits "that there may be ambiguity around article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic case law].
And the question might arise in the future as to the extent to which civilian judges are competent to rule on it."
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the former regime.
Another contentious point is the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the review of the defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will trials of civilians in military courts be prohibited, as requested by human rights associations.
The latter also expressed their concerns about the text, which they considered to be liberticidal.
The crime of blasphemy was maintained and insult was now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, particularly in the press.
In addition, there are no more articles that echo the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point was the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian President was due to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
The head of state's supporters will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of Bible truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argoumenty i Fakty has identified five main reasons for travelling to Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
A must-see: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that anyone who enters these "baptismal depths" will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he appeased the storm, or where the fishing was miraculous.
It was at this precise place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
The believers travel the Rue de la Souffrance or the Way of the Cross (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the pretoire), where the trial was held, then led through the streets of the old town to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the tomb.
This is where the Christian center of the world stands, symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to the Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations, which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 B.C.
According to tradition, people from different faiths leave small words with prayers there, which are then answered.
Travel high
Visit the ruins of the fortress Massada, former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 B.C. for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, lies the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you there from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth a visit.
First of all: the Museum of Israel located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the Judean Desert caves, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: the Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
The paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso are mainly exhibited.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of casts of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Yad Vashem Holocaust Museum or Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter in total darkness.
Stars are shimmering.
You then hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and welfare
Israel's three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each one offers swimming pools, water parks, delphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the temperature of the water does not fall below 21° while the temperature of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim there all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point of the Earth, i.e. 417 m below sea level.
The azure-coloured water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who cannot swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of surrealistic beauty.
We come to perform a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of Antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists especially like to stroll through the narrow alleyways that bear the name of the zodiac signs.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile on you.
In Jaffa you will be able to meet newlyweds who have come to make photo sessions of all Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "conquer" the fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, especially Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer the dollars to the euro, because they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar equals 3.8 shekels).
As far as urban transport is concerned, it is mainly the buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, composed of six stations and able to connect the lower and upper parts of the city.
It's almost an underground funicular.
The journey in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, the Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday night to sunset on Saturdays, markets, shops and public transport cease to operate.
And the working week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafés, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes made with lamb and beef, soups and desserts made with coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish dough, various sauces, ground chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats who walk around in the haughty air.
We can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars in the evening.
These felines love passing places and don't refuse to treat them.
The rental of a car varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24 hours (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 a day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
An entrance to the museum costs an average of 30 shekels.
The language of the figures
Three million tourists from around the world visited Israel in 2012.
They were mostly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists visited Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before the cancellation of visas on 9 February 2011.
"Who language has, in Moscow goes": migrants save money to learn the language
While MPs and human rights activists are arguing about what the law on mandatory language testing will give, fraudsters selling "false" certificates have already appeared in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Tajikistan, Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan.
Their only goal is to make money to help their families stay at home.
Since 1 December, a law had entered into force and stipulated that every migrant worker would have to pass a Russian examination.
For the time being, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the services, housing, personal services and retail sectors.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, the tests will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, knowledge of the language, but also of the history of Russia and the foundations of law, will have to be validated.
You will have to validate your knowledge of Russian in order to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained educational certificates or diplomas prior to the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not covered by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centres will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the University of Peoples Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other higher education institutions in Russia.
Immigrants will be able to take exams in all the cities of the country: more than 160 centres have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce examinations was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But before the law came into force, human rights defenders have asked the question in the press many times: what will it be?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, answer the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering "from slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, explains the director of the Russian Federal Migration Service office in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev certifies, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "travel" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellow men will torment themselves for months without food and paper and will have to work between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive numerous complaints from our migrants.
"There is one thing we promise them, and when they arrive, we deceive them, we take their passport, and they do not receive the salary they expect," confirms Tolib Charipov, Head of the Directorate of Migration Services for Labour of the Migration Service of Tajikistan.
Don't argue with me, officer!
However, many Central Asian republic nationals who wish to come to Russia to earn money say that they do not only not know the language of the country to which they wish to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford to attend even fair primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have enough to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people leave to earn money as soon as the opportunity arises.
It's difficult when you don't know the language, they confide.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
However, human rights defenders note an important aspect of the Language Act.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants with legal status.
Without a statute, there will be no formal examination or work thereafter.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live illegally in Russia.
"Welcome or Defence to Enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, you can get a fake recording quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we don't have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They ask us 100, 200 rubles, enough to buy cigarettes, tea", told journalists Umed Khushkadamov, a citizen of Tajikistan.
"Make it quick, don't skimp and buy yourself a beautiful piece of art"
On the first day of the entry into force of the Language Act, it was discovered that migrants' registration papers were not the only ones that were false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not have them for nothing: each migrant who thus hoped to facilitate the task of the examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Government representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term objective is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these "paper sticks".
The authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the examination on the first occasion the time to take language courses.
Moreover, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against civilian weapons carriers.
This is the reaction of the authorities to recent incidents: whether it is the shootings carried out during weddings or the killing organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, who killed seven people.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullet weapons in public places and raise the legal age for obtaining a licence to carry a weapon from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma's Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced in the State Duma shortly.
Not everyone is satisfied that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Net in which its authors, representatives of various firing centres, demanded to abandon "this insane hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, said Vasiliy Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC.
According to statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services while 1,168 thousand crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are certain that the strengthening of civil weapons laws will not prevent criminals from buying from the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow we can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior states that it controls the distribution of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to officer
The black arms market is supplied through several channels.
There are five main canals, says Victor Baranets, retired colonel who served ten years at the Ministry of Education and Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking arms commands
The first is the "military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," Baranets explains.
The second type of black market weapons are those stolen by criminals from law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go for sale from military warehouses.
Many of the latter have often suffered explosions.
"Attested versions indicate that some fires were deliberately triggered to cover up the deficit," says the former military officer.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are responsible for something.
"We see private arms factories that don't compete on the international market and sell weapons on the black market, especially in Moscow," one expert says.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a local production, sometimes craft production, a mafia has formed and organizes the supply," adds the former military.
Where did the weapons come from?
The experts assessed the approximate share of illegal weapons in the black market for each source.
A report on this issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Study for Public Administration.
Specialists analysed the reports of the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal files and public data on weapons portals.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "by fault of employees whose work is related to weapons", it is explained in the report.
According to the researchers, 17% of weapons come from military conflict sites, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "undercover searches".
A seller and consultant of an armory who asked to remain anonymous ensures that for a long time no one buys the weapons found by these secret search specialists; they are too old.
Most often, he says, sellers will pick up new goods from military warehouses.
The person buys a unit, such as a TT gun, through a sign.
We deliver it to him by passing the goods through a fence.
"He transports it to town and sells it for 900 € per unit with two chargers," he says.
"It is true that the police are aware of all cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a purchase of control from illegal arms dealers," the seller adds.
"Like in a luxury store"
The seller and buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I visited sites, blogs, until a guy showed up and offered me to come to the Begovaya train station where someone was going to take me in a "corner" to bargain.
The price of the gun, they gave it to me on the spot.
Victor Baranets as military observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the salesman. I know someone, but I don't trust him.
There are sellers on the markets, but there you have to come there also by saying, for example, "From such a person, who asked me to transmit that his daughter has lost a tooth".
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of someone I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them to him.
Newbies are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military member Victor Baranets tried himself as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, according to him, have not changed.
We gave him a photo album in which there was "everything we want."
"I thought I was in a luxury store," recalls the soldier.
There is no secret to the buyer, explains Baranets, we can try everything.
As a potential customer, I'm not just buying, we go with the forest salesman and set up a target.
"They let me shoot and when I'm convinced that the gun works well, we start negotiating," the expert describes.
A shop from his couch
Search engines display sites and groups on Vkontakte where you can buy weapons "for different uses".
