At the meeting of the supervisory committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you mentioned a Czech-German project in which the public procurement legislation of these two countries was compared.
What was the concrete question?
This is a parallel check that we launched about two years ago.
In simple terms, European legislation provides for how to manage public procurement and specific national legislation and a practice itself.
We have gathered all this together and although this monitoring procedure has not yet been completed, very interesting differences have arisen: generally speaking, our legislation may be "more severe and of better quality", but according to certain parameters, the practice itself is better in Germany.
This confirms, therefore, that it is not enough to draw up ever more detailed rules continuously, but that it is necessary to devote itself to the very implementation of the law.
How can this project help you in practice and what does it mean for you?
Common control of this kind should help us to stop trying to clarify laws, to lower and improve thresholds, where this does not have a really positive effect.
The principle of good management means getting the thing in question at a reasonable price (which does not always mean the lowest), in order to exclude any enrichment and possible criminal activity.
But lowering market thresholds will not necessarily achieve this objective.
It may be that this system is so overwhelmed by red tape that those looking for loopholes will find much more opportunities than if the threshold had remained higher.
