Šimon Ornest said: "In concert, we want to collect positive energy."
What do you think of the fact that in less than a month it should be the end of the world?
This is just one of those alarming news, the kind of traps we like to fall into.
In our band The Tap Tap, we laugh at it rather and we think that we are the only group able to collect a rest of positive energy in order to push back or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December you set up a completely unique project: three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you present this project in more detail to our readers?
It's a charity that we've been preparing for two years.
We decided to use the marketing potential of the end of the Maya calendar announced for December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before, on December 20, three concerts will take place simultaneously in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end almost at the end of the Mayan calendar on Kiribati Island in the Pacific Ocean, in a time zone 12 hours ahead of us.
Who had this idea?
At first I think it was my idea, then we designed everything with our creator, Honza Augusta.
Apart from the fact that we want to collect enough positive energy to save the world, we also want together, with the public, to reflect on the state of the world that we leave to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Maya calendar, we created a collection of unique objects, including shoes, T-shirts, bags, and original keys against the end of the world, by buying them online at www.e-tap.cz people can also support us.
The band The Tap Tap with other performers also recorded an anthem against the end of the world entitled "End of the World Cancelled " (in Czech " Konec světa zrušeno ").
She is already very popular on YouTube, will we hear her also at these charity concerts?
Of course, at the end, at last, if we succeed and the end of the world does not take place ...
It will be sung simultaneously by all the performers in all three concerts.
The anthems will also join at some point as part of a unique live programme on Czech television.
The lyrics of this song were written by Tom+ Hanák who also plays the main role of Jesus in the music video, Xindl X also sings...
How did you come to cooperate with them?
We collaborate with other personalities of the Czech show-biz, due to the fact that we organize numerous concerts and charitable events...
We strive to involve them intensively in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested in such cooperation and that it amuses them.
What will the benefits of these concerts against the end of the world be?
To equip the Studeo training centre, which is accessible to people with reduced mobility and which we have been working on as part of the Jedlička Institute, with the Tap association, for six years.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedličkův Institute and offer them activities that interest and amuse them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to classes, we try to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the construction of the Jedlička Institute, we will transfer this project to a new independent building.
Several music groups and performers will go on stage during each of these concerts?
According to what criteria, do you choose them?
We have tried to develop a program for all generations, including children.
For example, in Prague, Chinaski, Support Lesbians, Illustratosphere will stage with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Ji+ Suchý.
Full details can be found at www.kpks.cz.
Are you also preparing for other "mega events" of this kind in the future?
In May, we will play for the first time in the Prague Spring; here too, we will surely prepare a quality programme with interesting guests.
We would also like to play next year in the Czech Republic's house in New York and personally, once we're in the United States, I'd like to combine concerts in Washington and Chicago.
Your international projects are minimalist, so far you have played for example in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is, however, a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the organization and logistics of your tours?
It's not so bad that it looks like it at first.
We have five members in electric wheelchairs whose gear must travel in the hold, of course we also carry a lot of luggage and instrument boxes....
So far everything has gone more or less well, ČSA and British Airways were always perfectly prepared for us, they surprised me more than once.
Even in Moscow, from where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Thanks to your travel abroad, you can compare how these countries differ in terms of access facilities for people with reduced mobility, the attitude of public opinion towards people with disabilities and so on.
What have been your experiences so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than at home, we have just witnessed in Moscow that in the east all are still only in an initial phase.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is still very little accessible to people with disabilities; there, it is not yet common for a person to travel alone by electric wheelchair in the city centre.
They do not yet consider it obvious to give priority to a person in a wheelchair in an elevator.
Fortunately, there too, an association is being set up to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
How do we still have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There's a lot of things we're still late for...
It is important to note that improvements and improvements continue to depend on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite common for people with a heavy disability to travel alone in public spaces; they can go to the toilets, to the museum, anywhere...
It is not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities actively participate in social life, on this point you, The Tap Tap, are on the contrary at the cutting edge of progress!
Respect for the public and ease of access are one thing, but the situation will really start to change when we have among us famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers.
For the time being, these are only isolated cases of people who have a strong will.
The Tap Tap band is currently very popular, let's go back a few years, what led you in 1998 to create this band?
I started working as an educator at the Jedlička Institute, where I found myself surrounded by many young people willing to invest in something.
And since I am a musician myself (I play, among other things, saxophone), together with a colleague, we created a music activity.
And then, over time, as our moderator Lêa Angelovič says, we lost control of the situation a little bit (laughs).
Success has only happened in recent years, if I'm not mistaken?
It's true, creating links with known singers and actively working to promote the band helped us.
We understood that if a work is not visible, it is as if it does not exist in the background.
Thanks to EU subsidies, we can also afford quality teachers, equipment and so on.
Did you aim to achieve such a level with The Tap Tap?
From the beginning, I felt that there was potential to change things.
The show business is full of stuff that copy each other.
In a way, it makes sense: everything that is new is accepted with caution and it lasts a long time.
Rare are the original projects, and I dare say Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is naturally pity, it's natural ...
But pity is totally useless, because people with disabilities are not suffering beings, abandoned by all, whom we must take pity.
They are people who can live a full life and flourish, provided they have the necessary means, of course.
I often say that when people with disabilities achieve something, it is not just a step forward for them but for the whole of society.
Isn't your success also due to the fact that you are a demanding leader, as you are qualified by many people?
If we want to do quality work, we need to be intransigent in many areas and require some discipline.
But I think it's quite normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic vision and a head in the clouds and, when they realize that they have to come to rehearsals twice a week, take preparatory classes and spend a lot of time on the roads for concerts, they quickly lose their enthusiasm.
But it works the same way in every group that wants to work and achieve goals.
The Tap Tap group currently has 20 members.
How many of them were already there in 1998?
Only one, Lêa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people go in and out, we can't help it.
Our doors are always open to those who want or would like to join us.
This will be the case the day before the expected end of the world, Thursday, December 20, 2012 from 9 p.m.
