The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that the real adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is funny, it's very futuristic, at last something interesting to see," Lisette Verhaig tells us, a passerby on the side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist in a large neighboring company, tells us: "Yes, it is indeed beautiful, this building".
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has Internet, an iPad and e-books.
Today, no one is willingly going to one of these ringuard libraries anymore, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeper town that is not attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, has a rather special record.
The commune of 80,000 souls has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro notes in the form of pretty small miniatures of painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
Thus the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get their hands on statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, of the architect's office in Rotterdam MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a snitch on his face.
And while the members of the jury still looked at each other, disconcerted and shoving their shoulders, Maas, shocked him, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make them a pyramid, and finished his speech supported by militant arguments by a: "honey common!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the €30 million mountain sprang from the ground.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and adjoining houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the book mountain received the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project was selected for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Thus, this dull little town, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian zone and a town hall of a staggering uglyness, whose white facades invite to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
Most importantly, Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the cheese bell book.
True, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open to you when you walk down the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and the elegant lamps speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
"Normally, library shelves are located along the façade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We have completely changed the classic spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from inside to outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been skillfully arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes paneling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardened building do not want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," explains Joop Trouborst, project manager at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian farm.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membranes with a thickness of one millimetre have been used for years as substrates in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into four centimetres thick plates.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes colour and transforms into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, whose smell evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 metres, the literary café offers a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and potted ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to the maintenance of the ideal level of humidity of the air of the literary mountain.
Gifts for the new soul
"It's incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology," says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is set by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is under a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on days of fine weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted across from the glass façade serve as a sun visor, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Completely automated blinds handle the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there, too.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "recovered soul".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has made it possible to fill the gaps in the library which was not yet completely filled (today it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
This is how MVRDV has reached the master discipline which is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new page of literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans need to play a bigger role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer state status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but was not too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Does Germany have any difficulty in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore clashed with several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe they are still trying to find this role, but are on the way to a 'more normal' foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, thus by its exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the Middle East conflict and its abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to clash with public opinion, but also with the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, because it is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive factor in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps Germany will be even more respected.
Indeed, Germany has demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you observe the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overflowing with enthusiasm for Netanyahu's policy.
Does Germany find it difficult to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I don't think it makes things easier for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but this is not the case today.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
That is what they are currently doing about the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will play a locomotive role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been a delicate one.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware of the fact that they must play a more independent role.
Does Germany see itself playing a leading role on the international stage, does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or does it still have difficulty in taking on leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulties in playing a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
In fact, it's always the same problem: we don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
She has to deal with very diverse neighbours and opinions, and that's not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this void, so who remains?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America work together to analyse the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German policy, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well known brands around the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is an officially registered trademark in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that the undertaking bearing its name cannot lodge a complaint.
And even if she could, it is not certain that she would win the case.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," explains Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, a firm specializing in violating property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators only need a few additional letters to register their trademarks.
So instead of Gucci, we record Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, we record Prada-Kny.
German companies are also legally copied, such as Puma, the manufacturer of sports goods.
Pattloch opens a file containing the registrations made at the Beijing Trademark Office.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company filed the trademark Zegna DF Puma, a name that the company artificially created by owning part of the name Ermenegildo Zegna, the fashion house.
It is a well-known fact that the Chinese have become world champions of copying and infringement of intellectual property.
In large cities, there are multi-storey shopping malls that sell virtually nothing but counterfeits.
However, Pattloch's cases are different: his constituents charge him with tackling the fact that the Chinese Trademark Office officially grants Chinese companies the right to use a name that is already protected in another country.
The Chinese talk about "Bang Mingpai", a relative brand.
The term is derived from "Bang Dakuan".
It is with this term that women who marry rich men are referred to.
The Chinese authorities say they have nothing to blame for.
"It's bad for business, we have to fight this trend," Pattloch demands.
"The brand is sweetened, the singularity disappears, the damage to reputation is enormous."
Financial losses and legal costs amount to millions for the sectors concerned, especially with regard to expensive flagship products.
According to data from the analysis company of the market CLSA, China represents, with an annual volume of 15 billion euros, the third world market for luxury products and the fastest growing one.
However, it is not easy to remove questionable registrations from the trademark register and these procedures are expensive.
The latter can last for up to nine years, and the outcome is never certain.
Pattloch referred to the trials in which the court dismissed the complaint, because after a long period of time the term criticized had become a "market reality".
Pattloch explains to us that if the complainant is not lucky, he may even be forced to pay money to the plagiarist because he would have harmed his brand in China.
In this area, it is sometimes the law of the jungle that dominates.
Famous cases also concern graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal battle against the construction machine manufacturer Sany, the same company that had just bought the concrete pump producer Putzmeister.
That's why the Chinese can use an emblem that looks like the Mercedes star.
Geely, Volvo's successor, used a blue and white logo that resembled BMW's. The conflict was settled and Geely had to change it.
The Lacoste fashion house had lost against the plagiarists of Hong Kong and Singapore who had reoriented the gaze of the famous crocodile in the opposite direction.
According to the Chinese authorities, they are not guilty of anything.
However, the CTMO trademark office in Beijing admits to having experienced some difficulties in 2010 due to a lack of staff and space.
However, last year the Office would have moved from an "emergency situation in the course of work to a recovered normality".
Thus, the number of unprocessed opposition proceedings would have decreased by 22%.
Almost 57,000 cases of this type were reported to have been closed, an increase of 75% over the previous year.
Nevertheless, 81,500 proceedings remain outstanding at the Office.
It's expensive to act.
As is often the case in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
According to the Office, this is a record and it means that China is for the tenth consecutive time at the top of the ranking for the number of new deposits in the world.
This would also apply to the total number of legal trademarks, which is 5.5 million.
In 2011, the Office would have recorded 1.8 billion yuan of registration fees.
In other words, each record yielded an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
A legal battle costs much more, as illustrated by the case of the German family business Freudenberg.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
Of course, the Germans were able to obtain a suspension of the illegal manufacture of vehicle components.
However, the imitator was able to maintain its Chinese rights in the Freudenberg trade mark.
"It's our fault because last names cannot be protected in Germany," explains Hanno Wentzler, CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The trade mark office had therefore rejected the Munichers' objection.
Freudenberg has certainly won the case in the following two instances, but the opposing side continues to fight until today.
Vigilance is in order
Today, the case is pending before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler is confident, believes in a positive outcome of the trial and boasts the professionalism of the judges.
Nevertheless, he adds: "The procedure is long, difficult and costs us a lot of time and money."
It is also difficult to estimate internal costs. The Archives Service even had to review the records of the past 100 years in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg even proposed to the opposing party in vain a "big six-digit euro sum" to settle the dispute.
"That's what it means to us," Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East even threaten to spill over into Europe.
This would be the case if imitators in this region ensured the exploitation of unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese producer wanted to file in Germany the name Freudenberg for a shoe and leather production company.
The company had long abandoned this sector, but it had still been able to prevent the deposit.
Wentzler adds: "vigilance is in order".
Pattloch and he advise German companies to exercise great caution in their trade relations with China.
It is not enough, in their view, to rely on international trademark law, that foreigners should rather "register also in China anything that is likely to be protected", as Wentzler says.
Otherwise, the costs may be much higher than those of registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg lost the battle in the last act of its legal drama, the company would have to pay license fees to the opposing party for the use of its own name, as Wentzler explains.
Or we would lose our place in the segment of the market in question.
World AIDS Day: kicking, singing, helping
The Imbongi choir repeats in Heidelberg, and the AIDS orphans of Swaziland rejoice in their arrival.
This is the story of a link that crosses far more than a distance of 8,733 kilometers.
First, we kick: cowboy boots, sneakers, skids for ladies and moccasins for men look for the rhythm by hitting the floor of the foot. Very quickly, they find it.
One, two, three, four.
Then, the voices of the singers grow slowly - viola, bass, tenor and soprano - they get carried away, bewitch and follow each other.
Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old conductor, almost loses his canvas shoes when he directs the orchestra with his wildly flexible gestures.
It's Monday night, the Imbongi choir repeats a new song in the music room of the Heidelberg Institute of Medical Psychology.
Fifty singers and singers aged 23 to 69 have come, from the geneticist in human medicine to the man at home.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy song, each choir player has different lyrics, all in a very exotic language: Zulu, a language spoken by 11 million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and parts of Swaziland.
To be helped to help each other
UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS Programme, estimates that 34 million people worldwide are living with the disease.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
Swaziland has 245,000 infected people.
In addition, more than 40% of the population is HIV positive.
180 AIDS orphans from the village of Esitjeni found sponsors in Germany thanks to the "Voices for Africa" association.
70 of them attend secondary schools.
For 15 or 20 euros less, you can become a godfather.
This money guarantees the child money for school, a school uniform and a daily hot meal at the gogo centre.
Imbongi means in Zulu "story storyteller" or "singer of praise".
No one can speak the Bantu language fluently in this region, but all can sing it.
For almost 10 years, the choir has been rehearsing songs in this foreign language that it has brought to Germany to now return it to its native region: South Africa.
Because at 8,733 kilometers as the bird flies from Heidelberg, in the northwest of the Kingdom of Swaziland, is Esitjeni, the village that depends on the vocal power of the German choir.
40% of people affected
The village has about 2,000 inhabitants, some live in modest huts of straw or land and the majority of them are children.
More than 300 of them are orphans, as HIV has taken away their parents.
In Esitjeni, Swaziland's ills can be seen on a smaller scale: the highest rate of HIV infection and the lowest life expectancy in the world, according to UNICEF.
The population almost never accepts male circumcision, a measure that guarantees a proven reduction in the risk of infection by half.
More than 40% of Swaziland's population is infected with the immunodeficiency virus and it is not uncommon to die in the middle of their thirties.
During a group trip to Africa in the spring of 2005, the choir had been able to discover the village. Imbongis especially saw many children in the street who were missing not only parental care, but also simply everything: food, clothing, education.
In a poor country, without a school diploma, there is simply no perspective.
At first, they were only a few people who personally committed themselves to paying a few euros each year so that they could send a child to school and offer him a hot meal a day.
But just a year later, the choir founded "Voices for Africa", an association that has since almost professionally cared for AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, or hepatitis.
Pubis lice and scabies belong to parasitic STIs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and gonorrhea often occur in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert-Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are caused by sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydia-related infections, trichomonase, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhea and human papillomavirus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of spread of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, about 20% of new HIV infections are observed in this group.
In young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamydia-related infections than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections are among young people aged 15 to 25 years.
In addition, in Germany, human papillomavirus is common among young people.
What is the trend in the number of infections?
It is not mandatory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert-Koch Institute, the number of syphilis cases has more than doubled in 10 years: the number has increased from 1,967 in 2001 to 3,698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been declining.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one-tenth over the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual disease?
Infectious diseases can cause genital abscesses, urinary pain, white discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, and the appearance of pimples and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How can we protect ourselves?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect 100%.
The reason for this is that sexually transmitted disease pathogens can also be transmitted by lubricating infection or by close bodily contact.
The experts therefore recommend that any person who often changes sexual partners take regular exams.
Most rapidly detected STIs can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
