A survey of a country, in which we are still relatively young at 97.
The journey through the Talysh Mountains is a complete romanticism.
At the turn of the many turns of the road, the small bus cahoots along wooded hills, torrential rivers and modest farms.
It's all green and fertile, it's almost like the Black Forest.
But here we are in the deep south of Azerbaijan, the border with Iran is only a few kilometres away.
This is where the Caucasian ethnic group, called Talysh, lives, about which we do not know much, except that they speak perfectly Persian and Azeri and that they have a very long lifespan.
Terminus: Lerik.
The small town plastrons with its too aggressive architecture of the Soviet era which does not at all agree with the picturesque mountain landscape.
European tourists are rare here, the journey from Azerbaijan's capital, Baku, is far too painful.
It takes eight hours to travel the 323 kilometers, because the road has only one lane.
The province has not yet benefited from the legendary wealth that the country owes to its oil reserves in the Caspian Sea.
However, 48-year-old Pilata Fatulayeva is convinced that Lerik has the potential to become a tourist destination.
"Baku became famous in May thanks to the Eurovision competition, and next year there will be the festival of the oldest people in the world," Fatulayeva explains.
She is the director of the museum of longevity, the only museum of its kind in the world.
We can discover the lives of about eight dozen Talysh of the region who are more than 100 years old. Fatulayeva shows us a black and white photo.
This is my grandfather, he's 120 years old.
Have one more child at 136 years old
But the controversial star of the museum is Şirali Müslümov, a shepherd who would have been 168 years old.
However, there is no birth certificate.
And when one thinks that the oldest documented person was 122 years old, the age of Müslümov seems more than doubtful.
"He was born in 1805 in this region, he died in 1973," Fatulayeva says.
The man would have married three times and had 23 children. At the age of 136, he would still have conceived a daughter.
Would Şirali Müslümov have been wrong for a few decades in calculating his age?
Rembrandt Scholz, a gerontologist at the Max Planck Institute in Rostock, also heard of the man of the great age of Central Asia.
"Amazingly elderly people also live in parts of China, Japan or the Hunza Valley in Pakistan," Scholz explains, "also in Sardinia, there are men who live incredibly old."
However, it is impossible to establish scientific evidence due to the lack of documentation, and there was no civil registry.
Every day, a glass of melted butter
However, it is true that people in the Lerik area often reach an age worthy of the patriarchs of the Bible.
Currently, 20 people are over 100 years old.
So what is the reason for longevity in the south of this country?
Farid Mugimzadeh, the Azeri tourist guide, explains that the Talysh have particular genes.
However, Fatulayeva, the director of the museum, thinks it is a matter of food.
However, from a nutritional point of view, it does not seem plausible that the high-calorie meals of the Talysh, which love meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of which drink daily a glass of melted butter, are good for their health.
Or is it the simple way of life that preserves the youth of people? In Cengemiran, a tiny village close to the city of Lerik, lives Rubaba Mirzayeva.
At the age of 97, she is still relatively young for the region.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 descendants, lives in a modest wooden house, as it is typical to see throughout the Caucasus region.
She sits on the ground next to a bar, whose content she beats tirelessly.
Eight people live here under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva's sons and one daughter, who have long been adults.
Two little children are also swarming in the house.
In the kitchen, tea is prepared for guests served in typical armadus glasses in the shape of a belly.
Mirzayeva's white teeth are perfectly aligned, and under his scarf hide long braids of a dark blonde whom his son proudly reveals to us.
I've always washed my hair with milk, and that's how I never lost them and they kept their color.
"I've never used shampoo," Mirzayeva adds.
Monthly pension is enough to live
She has always eaten what comes from her own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
I've never bought anything in a supermarket in my whole life.
Then she tells us about her husband who was in the army.
The worst moments were after World War II.
But everything improved when "beloved father" Heydar Aliyev took over.
The language of propaganda is astounding in the mouth of an old lady.
However, the cult of the paternal figure of the nation, a man who has led his country as a dictator, knows almost no limits in Azerbaijan.
He was in power until 2003, after which his son Ilham succeeded him.
In any case, the elderly people of Azerbaijan do not know the distress.
Mirzayeva receives 230 manats (about the same amount as in euros) monthly for his retirement, a sum that guarantees a good lifestyle in the region.
And perhaps Mirzayeva's long-graying son is right: "the elders enjoy great respect in our culture".
They are the center of the big family, they are loved, cared for and happy.
That's a good reason to live as long as possible.
The “human rights” omitted from the Constitution
The revolution is reborn in Cairo.
Opposite demonstrations reveal the deep fracture of the country.
The draft constitution based on sharia law is violently controversial.
The Egyptian President is not stupefied by words full of emotion.
We must succeed in the transition.
"And this success is my responsibility to the people and to God," he declared on state television.
His speech was intended for the entire people, but also especially for Christian Copts, Liberals, enlightened Muslims and lay people.
Because all members of the confused and desperately disunited opposition are afraid.
They are afraid of a theocracy on the Nile in the hands of the powerful Muslim Brotherhood.
Mohamed Morsi said, almost by apologizing, that he had temporarily restricted the powers of the Constitutional Court and expanded its powers "in order to save the revolution".
However, the Egyptians and the world do not really know what this 61-year-old engineer wants to save, who holds a PhD from the American University of Southern California.
Will the judiciary be overthrown?
The 234 hastily written articles by the predominantly Islamic Constituent Assembly of 100 people during a 15-hour night tour of power are indeed disturbing to some extent.
As in previous constitutions, the draft provides that jurisprudence is based on "the principles of Islamic law".
But what does the word "principles" really mean?
It was and still remains a question of interpretation, and there is good reason to fear that Islamists will use the vague wording and the resulting legal leeway to apply a stricter interpretation of sharia law.
In any case, it is suggested by a newly introduced article stipulating that, with regard to all matters relating to Shariah, al-Azhar University must be consulted. The institution is the most important Islamic institution in the country and its brilliance radiates throughout the Sunni Islamic world.
This may, but does not necessarily mean that the clergy will monitor the legislative machinery, which would de facto lead to the guardianship of the judiciary.
Many points of the draft Constitution are subject to interpretation.
Another problematic aspect is the likely continuation of military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak's reign, these courts tried to repress the opponents.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were detained by the military.
The project also states that the State must protect "the true nature of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values".
From a legal point of view, the wording is so vague that state institutions could even control the content of cinematographic art and literature.
In short, it would simply be censorship.
Moreover, there is no article that expressly guarantees equality between men and women.
Instead, another article forbids offending or defaming the Prophet Muhammad or his envoys.
However, the article does not define what an offence is or how it should be punished.
Equally dubious is the wording implying that it is forbidden to "offend people".
Is it enough to draw a cartoon of the president or to tell a joke to the detriment of a lawman?
Many points are therefore subject to interpretation in the draft which Morsi put to the vote and which, in his own words, will be the subject of a referendum with the Egyptians "very soon".
"The Revolution Reborn"
The opposition has been mobilizing for weeks against the numerical superiority of Islamists.
On Friday evening, tens of thousands of protesters gathered in an unusual concord on Tahrir Square in Cairo, promising to bring down the sharia before it enters into force.
"The revolution is reborn and we will win," says Hamdin Sabbahi, who came third in the presidential elections.
Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency Mohamed El Baradei said the draft Constitution is "to be thrown into the trash of history".
On Twitter, the instant messaging service, he accused Morsi's supporters of wanting to foment a "putsch against democracy".
"If he proclaims the referendum, we will go to his palace and overthrow him," exclaims Jasser Said, an opponent.
"We are not yet tired, the blood of our brothers is not yet atoned," said Egyptian media Khaled Ali, a politician and member of the opposition.
