The problem is that it has been defined, and debated, in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, Associate Professor of Psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After going through many publications and submitting the idea to a focus group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as "an experience of wanting to do something, but without getting into a satisfactory activity."
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task although he or she would like to do so.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of the boredom, he said, is "the interruption of the attention process, associated with a wretched mood and the feeling that time passes slowly."
The boredom can look very much like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while both can be related, bored people tend to think that the problem comes from the environment or the world, while depressed people think that the problem comes from them.
Sometimes we think we're bored when it's actually a concentration problem.
As part of their study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention", which was published in the journal "Perspectives on Psychological Science" in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an earlier experience in which participants listened on tape, the voice of a person reading a magazine article.
