The hardest job in the world: Kawah Ijen's human mule
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their life and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone paths.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by carrying the sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where sulphuric gas emanating from the earth's entrails solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulphur rocks, which weigh a total of nearly 70 kilos, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There are only 250 meters up to the summit of the volcano which peaks at 2,386 meters of altitude, but the exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle's pace, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the volcano Kawah Ijen several years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once at the top, he makes a path between tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying the heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the scale that a mining company installed a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) per kilo of sulphur.
She then sells it to the petrochemical industry for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes him 3 hours and he finishes exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what it would gain in the fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", says the bearer who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) a day and the job wasn't as difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hinduists, and I brought her back to Java to convert to Islam."
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and her eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulfur has already begun to charge him the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and her eyes are irritated by toxic gases released by the volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
"I'm going to work for another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in English more than acceptable.
Misled by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tourist guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy wood massure with other carriers, rises every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not cease to spring at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the middle of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by lighting himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulphur extraction to save costs and does not provide equipment to self-employed carriers who are paid by weight.
Moreover, they also do not receive one sous of the 30,000 rupees (2,50 euros) of increase per camera, in addition to the entry of 15,000 rupees (1,20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge to the tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
"This work is done for animals, not for humans," protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old carrier who has been working in Kawah Ijen for thirty years since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", because he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulphur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual breathing problems, arthroses, pains in the knees and shoulders, distorted by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53 years old, can only load 50 kilos.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometres away by a weed-infested goat trail.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik says, opening her mouth well, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult trades in the world: that of the human mules of the Kawah Ijen volcano.
Singapore seeks babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame this lack of children for the career, stress and cost of access to property.
"Singapore's population must grow."
I'm a husband and a patriot, you're my wife and a patriot, let's fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem improbable that these words come from an advertisement for mint lozenges, but despite that, or perhaps because of that, the video spread like a dust trail on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's put a prank in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way thanks to this advertising.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to ensure that people fulfill "their national duty."
It is intended only for the Internet, so we were able to make it entertaining and fun.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt that it was a theme that we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things, such as throwing perfumes at pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of these ideas were creative but did not necessarily work.
So we said the following: what more creative to solve this problem than to make it a rap song?
1.2 children
The Singapore government is not taking it as lightly.
He spends US$1,300 a year on politics to encourage his citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favour of marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, increases maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
Singapore ' s birth rate, in line with its national population distribution, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the renewal rate, was in 1976.
Why, then, do Singaporeans not have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policies of the National Population Division, says it is due to "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities".
"This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and family building," she explains.
These changes in social standards have contributed to an increase in the number of singles and to delays in marriage and birth, resulting in a decline in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter the decline in the population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound in barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially against Chinese who are accused of drawing wages down and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party experienced its worst election results since independence last year.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in specific areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they can promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, general manager of the real estate company EL Developers, says that its "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these dwellings are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to the developers, who were previously put sticks in the wheels if they wanted to offer too many small housing units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new regulations may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by discussing with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the centre, it would appear that they are not going to have much effect.
"People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, which is why people postpone it," says a young executive.
Other people can have children.
"But for me, it is important to have my money and my time," another young man, about twenty years old, tells us.
Men and women refer to their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons why they cannot have children.
Thus, while the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to baby-making, Singaporeans themselves have the final say.
What is private offline is private online
Confidentiality
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy, this is the quality of the private domain or "the domain of private life that we can protect from any intrusion".
What is the private domain for those under 16 years of age?
How can this definition be applied in everyday life and on social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces by broadcasting events on the Internet that he would certainly not share offline?
The newspaper elPeriódico interviewed five young boys, between the ages of 10 and 15, who were frequent users of the web.
In four of the cases, they associated the term "something very personal" on a personal level with "password and username" when they applied it to social networks.
"I won't reveal my most personal secrets in a post," says Jorge, ten years old, when he tries to explain the meaning of the private term on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had an account for two years.
"These are very secret secrets, my mother can know them but not everyone," he says.
On FB, I post nice pictures or games.
I'm also talking to my friends.
"I won't share one of my photos or someone who's making the fool," he says.
The boy acknowledges that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, naked people, crimes or to write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge assures that he knows his 35 friends on FB as well as his nine followers on Twitter.
The majority are family members.
Her mother is one of them, she knows the password of one of the accounts.
I opened a Twitter account to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just post them," he adds.
"Social media is fun, I can talk to distant relatives or friends, quickly," he says.
He claims that he would never accept the request of an unknown person.
Nor will he trust someone who would recommend a stranger to him.
José's case, 14, is different.
The teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, on the latter he admits not to know 20 of the people registered on his list of friends.
"It doesn't worry me because we have something in common, music for example," he says.
According to the boy, no one made any advances or asked him for his address or telephone number.
"If they put pressure on me or demanded it, I would simply remove them from my account," he admits.
José subscribed to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The experiences we know today under the name of cyber-harassment are no stranger to the young boy.
A relative of one of my friends was racked on a social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
"He never knew who it was," he said.
The victim, according to José, didn't close his account.
"He only put it in a private profile."
He then explains a series of manipulations to configure his account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this young man would post photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would if I was angry or angry.
"Even though I know it's cyber-harassment," he says.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, an English teacher and a graduate in Education and Learning, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet has emerged as a way to look for information but, with the appearance of these sites, the rule of the game has changed," she says.
Porras reports that academician Marc Prensky, who holds a Master's degree in pedagogy from Yale University and author of the book "Natives and Digital Immigrants", uses these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital natives are they, children and young people who were born with technology.
"We are the digital immigrants who have to teach them there, while we are learning ourselves," she says.
He added that the theme was complex, "because we ask them to have a definite criterion on what should or should not be disclosed, published or said at an age when they do not have the maturity to do so".
"We also ask them to be selective when what matters most to them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," she adds.
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents about confidentiality is to use questions that make them think.
"Their saying not to do so is of no use," she says.
Then Porras lists some examples: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, why are you doing it on the Internet?
Or would you like them to publish a picture of you like that of a friend you published?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you identify holiday photos, do you ask other people for permission to identify them?
And also, does everyone need to know what you're doing every moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online as they do offline.
They're the same rules.
"Outside the Internet, everyone must act with respect, morality and other principles, it must be the same on social networks," she says.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and education advisor, says it is essential that parents carefully read the conditions for using social networks.
By understanding each term, they will have a solid basis for discussing with their children the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
"For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or published," he says.
According to Guardia, it is essential to remind children not to talk to foreigners.
The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was announced earlier and theoretically adopted by the seven representatives present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the closure of the summit, and then said that it would be published from one moment to the next on the website of the Peruvian government.
When questioned about the text, they reported that its contents had been explained by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The lack of information among journalists was reported by press officers of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document disclosed during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media calling for more important information.
Later, the presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd South America-Arab Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested with the press, it had also not circulated the statement also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official ASPA website, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to set up safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited the gathering of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which settles a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and stated that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both sides in the Lima trial against Santiago which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes we are bringing before this international court today," said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals," added President Piñera, giving a handshake to President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had denounced this week the Pact of Bogotá by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua which it considered to be gravely wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President, Ollanta Humala, was instructed to open the deliberations in the morning and close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million in investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "important steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions to improve access to medicines, access to low-cost Internet throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should help increase our productive matrix and see a better future for our people," President Humala concluded.
"We decided to favour a group of 31 emblematic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Of these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on its territory's transversal routes, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not provide further details.
Similarly, the outcome document referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that this country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and with good relations with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, declared, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his counterpart from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to revise all these avenues, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua which will ask for a discussion with that country," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible," added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the takeover of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Similarly, in the framework of the summit, the Bloc Defence Ministers will meet in advance to endorse the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of Unasur, although it is suspended.
Peru assumed the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
"South America needs to learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship," says Rafael Correa.
The President of Ecuador, Rafael Correa, said today that the creation of a common citizenship is an objective for which "South America, in this case, should take an example on Europe".
President Correa, who attended the 6th Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), in Lima, said on state television, TV Péru, that Europeans "had killed each other during the Second World War" and other conflicts, "but now they were almost a homeland".
In this sense, he defended the project to establish South American citizenship encouraged by the member countries of Unasur.
"It is necessary to achieve the free movement of citizens and workers in any South American country, as is already the case for the members of the Andean Community, but there are still reactionary areas that we want to make belong to the past," he warned.
In addition, the President of Ecuador expressed his support for the reconstitution of the Organization of American States (OAS) with the objective of diminishing the influence of Anglo-Saxon States and taking into account the signatories of the San José Pact on Human Rights.
Those who beat our ears never compromise anything, but we, the South Americans, have all signed it.
"It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights is in Washington under US funding," he said, referring to Ecuador's political asylum granted to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
Correa assures that he does not regret his decision, because he himself did not betray his principles, but instead respected his "profound democratic values and human rights".
He concluded that at the time, "there were well-founded suspicions that Assange would be extradited to a third country and that his trial would not be respected."
In addition, he criticizes the Swedish courts for requiring him to submit to an interrogation in his territory concerning an alleged sexual offence, while "Swedish legislation allows him to do so by videoconference, which could be done from the Ecuadorian Embassy in London".
Correa stated that there is a risk that Assange's mental and physical health will deteriorate.
"I haven't talked to him since he was in our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he had a small lung problem, but nothing serious," said the Ecuadorian president.
It is possible that his physical and mental health deteriorates by being locked in a small space without being able to exercise in the open air.
"It acts on the health of anyone," he concludes.
Correa points out that the asylum solution granted to Assange since June in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, which would be the award of a safe-conduct to allow him to go to Ecuador, is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities and points out that he had discussions in London to find a solution to the confinement of the founder of WikiLeaks.
We are not negotiating with human rights, we are not using that word in this case, but there have been ongoing discussions.
"The solution to this problem lies in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European judicial authorities because Assange's lawyer, Baltazar Garzón, has launched a whole series of proceedings in various European bodies," he mentioned.
And he thinks that "if Britain were to grant safe conduct tomorrow, it would end."
And if Sweden, as its legislation quite permits, and as it has already done in other cases, questioned Mr Assange in the Ecuadorian embassy in London, or questioned him via Skype tomorrow, the problem would also be solved.
Correa took the opportunity to reaffirm himself as a defender of press freedom and said that what he did not tolerate was "the mediocrity, bad faith and lies that undermine freedom of expression".
"The biggest enemies of press freedom are not the evil or perverse politicians but the bad journalists on account of greed, blackmail and extortion," he said.
From this point of view, he welcomed the fact that this is not the kind of journalists "neither the bankers nor the hegemonic and bourgeois countries that dominate Ecuador" and, rather than putting forward his re-election, "he would deepen the revolution to pursue the path and chart the right path".
Correa also supported the decision to maintain the veto on Paraguay in the Unasur at least until the next elections, arguing that the organization "should be firm and not tolerate opportunism and disguised coup attempts", because in reality, "this was destroying the legitimacy of Paraguayan democracy".
Moreover, the President of Ecuador considers as "perfectly relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgment of the International Court of The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgment is not respected.
It is a problem between a South American and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
We must solve them as a whole in order to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed confidence in the successful resolution of the dispute concerning the maritime borders between Peru and Chile in the same court and stated that it is "benefiting that Latin America will take up international proceedings if the two countries agree to accept a judgment however firm it may be".
Referring to the possibility of his nomination as a candidate for the upcoming presidential elections in Ecuador, with a view to running for a third consecutive term, he pointed out that he saw this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that if he lost the primarys of February 2013, he would withdraw from public life.
At the personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unfair as those of Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can only be resolved through political power.
"My political movement believed that it was me who guaranteed this eventual victory, but we must accept this responsibility," he said.
If I won, it would be my last presidential term and then I will withdraw from political life.
If we ever lose, I will, too.
"It's my decision," he said.
Correa also referred to the new medical treatment of Venezuelan President Hugo Chávez in Cuba.
I just talked to Venezuelan Vice President Nicolás Maduro and he told me that routine medical treatment was already planned and that he was waiting for the end of the campaign to return to Cuba.
"This does not mean a relapse in President Chávez's health," he commented.
The Ecuadorian Head of State participated today in Lima at the Sixth Summit of Heads of State and Government of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur), which ended with a call for better regional integration to support progress, equality and security.
AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 when he was confirmed with the HIV test.
"It was as if the sky had fallen on my head," he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make "less painful", in vain.
The young man hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness on his own and began to inquire about him and his strenuousness was such that he has just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there was a lot of doubt, little choice of treatment and more stigma.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he was speechless."
In those days, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, in all cases after the first reported cases, "the great victory is today that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same", said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva and he takes for reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
HIV/AIDS infectiologist and expert Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a fatal disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of immune system allocation that patients have at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years for a CD4 rate of 200 and up to 50 years for those who reach a rate of 500 CD4.
To put it simply, it means that for someone who is diagnosed with HIV positive at age 25, "as long as he remains under control, he can live without problems up to age 75," explained the interviewed scientist.
In order to put this progress in context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years on average.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died as a result of AIDS has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the annual report of UNAIDS), it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60% of patients registered on the national data basis have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May of this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
Then why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over the last 12 years at least, we have never lacked medication, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact that "nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, to do so, we must offer screening tests on a massive scale, to all those who ask for it".
Specialists and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (Coesida) agree with his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and because, despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better if I have fun three times a week," they say.
The change has been beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he is suffering from cancer.
I have a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, thanks to his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the march of World AIDS Day.
If they've taken risks, the sooner they'll know if they're HIV positive, the better, and if they're already diagnosed, they need to know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programmes and the ordinary citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the greatest is prevention.
In all places dedicated to this, "the distribution of condoms has actually been increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, it is very good, but it results, that still today, some do not have access to condoms," he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", asked with sarcasm and value judgments by social workers, guidance counsellors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers don't want to hear, says the journalist.
It proposes to reorient this inefficient distribution; that condoms not only be sold at counters, but be found in public toilet dispensers and in places frequented by young people.
It is not about encouraging promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio González replied when asked whether there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
"This is not how sexuality works, the best is to provide condoms to people already sexually active," he stressed.
The figures in Jalisco
There are 13.435 cumulative cases (12.158 AIDS and 1.317 HIV).
The State is the fourth largest state in the country in terms of the number of new cases and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th largest in terms of the number of people living with HIV.
92% of infections occur by sex, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV, since for every registered case, there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a US court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt through commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario sets a bad precedent for all national companies with branches in the neighbouring country and with solvency problems.
It therefore seems that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican law are not valid in the country with the starry banner, contrary to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgement handed down on 15 June by Judge Harlin Hale of the Court of Bankruptcy for the Northern District of Texas leaves Mexican companies defenceless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico's leading glass manufacturer to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court based on three inconsistencies.
First, while the trial judge notes that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal, based in New Orleans, states that the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
Indeed, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been created for that purpose by taking the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that without the intercorporate vote, recognised in the critical mass of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by Vitro's subsidiaries towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, Vitro's case is not the first to use this plan.
Here there are half a dozen examples, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose debts were guaranteed by the Federal Institute of Commercial Bankruptcy.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the votes of the subsidiaries remained, in any case the creditors of Vitro who fought against this in the courts of the United States, i.e. the "vulture" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained a majority.
The vote would have been 45 to 37.
A data omitted by the appellate court.
On the other hand, Vitro has been blamed for the difficult situation he has encountered since 2008 without stopping at the serious economic crisis facing the United States, passing on the costs to the country.
For the time being, the González Sada family society will appeal to the same court of appeal so that the vote can take place in its entirety, i.e. with the five magistrates, since only three had voted.
The insurance remedy will demand non-prosperity and requires review of the trial by a higher court, in this case the Supreme Court of Justice of the United States.
The most serious is that the court ignored a document sent by the Mexican government on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the Court") in which Vitro's procedure under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act was detailed, noting that this freed him from the agreements signed by both countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he noted that the country had adhered to the United Nations Commission on International Trade principles, i.e., the rules for cross-border insolvency cases, which ensured fairness for debtors and creditors.
Carambolage of two parts: they stomp Vitro and they stomp the country.
General review
