Héctor "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The globetrotter of basketball "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, travelled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for over 60 years, whether as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I have worn several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," recalls Reyes during a visit of Primera Hora to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that recall his unusual itinerary, bear witness to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loved most were those who reminded him of his career as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"It was my best years, the ones I took the most advantage of because I had the chance to compete in eight Vaqueros championships from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or manager.
It's been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and who was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), told me: "I have a strong player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
That's how to start Mincy, one of Puerto Rico's best players.
Bartow then recommended Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win one championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He was delighted with the Vaqueros championship with Gausse, but only remotely since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's positions on the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we arrived in fourth place and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn't had us play the last game again," said Reyes.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as was the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite was that of the 1991 Cuban Pan American Games, when we won the gold and we beat the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter, the brothers León (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world 90 because of a knee problem.
A team that may not have been the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén in Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the suspended players with the improglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we won gold against all the predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Undoubtedly, it is Piculín Ortiz.
His statistics on international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated at this level like Piculín did.
And this without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious time of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that by the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What is left for you to do?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of the minor categories.
For example, Ponce's boys play only in their area and play only teams from other parts of the island during national play-offs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when this is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the advantage of mandatory certifications and courses for managers, field staff and referees.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch videos of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, attend basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide by the leading role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died Friday night of complications of cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in her dear hometown of Dallas, playing again the ironic role he loved the most," said the family.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who interpreted his wife's role in the original series and in the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said his press secretary, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived his life to the full," Gray said in a statement.
The doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and he had admitted that he had been drinking a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignancy in the liver and had been transplanted.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary type in the series "Jinny de mes rêves" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he interpreted the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, interpreted by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also appeared in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
Among her roles in the cinema are well received roles by critics in "Le bande", "Harry et Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the deliciously detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives was aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, generated speculation all over the world and millions of dollars played in bets.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the response was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (interpreted by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had pregnant her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave town, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) interned.
"I know what it would take to epitaph J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Ci-gite the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-prototheist of the original series, recalled this Friday of Hagman as a man " immense, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of all of us, who have had the chance to know and love it.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the channel TNT.
The recording of five episodes is already finished for the second season and a sixth is in progress, informed the channel.
For the time being, neither Warner nor TNT have communicated on how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
