A course on the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when the professor of religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a lecture on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching there an irresistible hook: the end of the "big count" of the Maya calendar, on December 21, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a fiscal abyss that some dubbed "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end times thought the apocalypse would trigger.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé to his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And it must be remembered that what is evil is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher to lecture on "the end of the world" this semester, which will be, in theory, the last in history.
In Temple, assistant professor Barry Vacker gives the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World".
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides some human conduct.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real life examples.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," said Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply entitled "The End of the World".
"We add "2012" to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world does not disappear," said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students have to study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be on the eve of the Apocalypse, which leaves students no choice but to work "until the very night of the end of the supposed world," said Restall.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
"It was complete in two hours," said Restall about his course for high-level students, made up of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the semester began, from people who asked if there was still room.
The students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinates me to see what people can do to comfort themselves," says 23-year-old religious and sociology student Bridgid Robinson from Haddonfield, New Jersey, Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of Revelation, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or of lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in Psychology and Infirmary, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic films.
"I had never heard of a course that taught this subject," he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a professor, told us that they believed the end of the world on December 21.
"Our first project dealt with Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it," says Julie zegle, a 21-year-old Temple student from West Chester.
The Mayas have never predicted the end of the world, it is only a key date on the calendar, said Restall.
But I concede that there is an anxiety related to the apocalypse in Western culture, dating back several centuries, that makes people react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has led to a rise in speculation.
"In other parts of the world, people don't think about it," he says.
This is mostly the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that classes were being given here on "the end of the world".
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years we have talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or thinking about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a period of 7 years at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many have told us that they are thinking of going to "end of the world" parties.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh at them together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
